answer: @alexanoid Sort of... The key here (pun unintended) is the node lookup part. Using only the map check, you have to go through every node, check if they id is a key in the map, and check the value. If you pull up the nodes like (psudocode) id(node) IN map.keyset(), than you no longer have to pull every node for the map[node.id] exists check. Cypher is a descriptive language though, so hiding things in a map makes it harder for Cypher to plan a more efficient query. So a map will never quite be equivalent to another query format. (except when you do a full loop over it)

embedfield:
mongodb - Multiple Compound Indexes involving a common field

We have a collection with millions of data. This data is being rendered in the UI for stats purpose and hence time to render is of key importance.

The queries to render the data involve the below fields:

  1. field_a and field_t
  2. field_b and field_t
  3. field_c and field_t

As we are querying millions of data, we want to use Compound Index to speed up the queries.

To do so, we can simply add 3 different compound indexes as below:

db.mycollection.createIndex( { "field_a": 1, "field_t": 1 }
db.mycollection.createIndex( { "field_b": 1, "field_t": 1 }
db.mycollection.createIndex( { "field_c": 1, "field_t": 1 }

ESR rule is respected while creating the indexes as field_a, field_b and field_c are equality checks and field_t is a range check. Please note that field_t is common in all the 3 indexes.

Instead of creating 3 different indexes, is there a better approach to this?

Does mongo provide a more efficient way to handle this scenario where same field is being used in multiple compound indexes?

Using $oid with MongoDB Atlas, Data API and updateMany

I'm trying to run an updateMany command with the Mongo Atlast Data API, but I can't figure out how to use $oid against an array of _ids. The workaround I landed on was

filter: { $or: _ids.map(_id => ({ _id: { $oid: _id } })) },

Is there a way to get a variation on one of these to work, though?

filter: { _id: { $in: { $map: { input: _ids, as: "$oid" } } } },
// or
filter: { _id: { $in: { $oid: _ids } } },
answer: i assumed that re.escape does the escaping part. Instead of manually escaping every special character in the future.
